{
  "card_id": "trend_line",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Trend Line",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "General",
  "definition": "A straight line drawn on a price chart connecting at least two consecutive swing lows (uptrend) or swing highs (downtrend) to identify trend direction and slope, acting as dynamic support or resistance and often forming boundaries of chart patterns like triangles.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "For an uptrend, connect at least two consecutive higher swing lows (pivot lows).",
    "For a downtrend, connect at least two consecutive lower swing highs (pivot highs).",
    "The line should touch the swing points without significantly cutting through candle bodies.",
    "Use a pivot point indicator or visual inspection to locate swing highs and lows.",
    "Ensure the line has multiple touches (price bounces) to confirm validity; adjust to fit as many swing points as possible.",
    "To form a trend channel, draw a parallel line opposite the trend line connecting swing highs in an uptrend or swing lows in a downtrend.",
    "Trend lines can outline chart patterns by connecting price extremes (e.g., upper and lower boundaries of triangles)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Trend lines act as dynamic support or resistance, where price tends to bounce. A decisive break below an uptrend line or above a downtrend line signals a potential trend reversal or acceleration, prompting traders to consider entry or exit decisions.",
